1. Pick your problem and explain the prediction problem ¶

rubric={points:3}

In this mini project, you will be working on a classification problem of predicting whether a credit card client will default or not. For this problem, you will use Default of Credit Card Clients Dataset. In this data set, there are 30,000 examples and 24 features, and the goal is to estimate whether a person will default (fail to pay) their credit card bills; this column is labeled "default.payment.next.month" in the data. The rest of the columns can be used as features. You may take some ideas and compare your results with the associated research paper, which is available through the UBC library.

Your tasks:

  2. Download the dataset and read it as a pandas dataframe.

Our task is to predict whether a client will default on their credit card bill or not. Both the number of examples and number of features are quite large relative to the ones we've worked with before. All of the columns are numeric, but looking more carefully we can see some features that are more categorical, such as "MARRIAGE", "PAY_X" and "SEX". These will be investigated in more detail later on.

Looking at the counts of 1s versus 0s in our "default.payment.next.month" column, we see that we have many more examples of non-defaulting clients than defaulting ones, which makes sense. This class imbalance is not going to pose much of a problem, we will just need to be more considerate in choosing our scoring method. Since we don't have exact specification from the bank (our client), we will choose to score our model using recall, as we want to make sure we identify as many people that will default as possible.

Summary of EDA:¶

  • We found that all of our columns are filled in, which means we won't need to use an imputer when preprocessing our data
  • We also identified that all of our columns are numeric, although some features are actually encoded categorical features, so we will need to separate those from the normal numeric columns.
  • We also looked at the target and realized that we have some class imbalance. Because of this, we should not use accuracy as a scoring metric. We instead decided to use recall, as the bank would likely want to limit as many potential defaulters from applying for credit. To further this point, we decided to set our classifiers to use class_weight="balanced" to ensure that the positive cases (will default) are weighted more heavily.
  • We also looked at the distributions of each feature to help us get an idea of which features will provide more value than others, which may come in useful when we are training our models. The distributions also helped us identify some of the numeric features that were actually categorical.
  • Similarly, we looked at the heatmap of the correlations between features. This was done in an attempt to understand how much each feature interacts with the other features so that we could potentially plan out some form of feature engineering.

# From lecture 2
def mean_std_cross_val_scores(model, X_train, y_train, **kwargs):
    """
    Returns mean and std of cross validation
    """
    scores = cross_validate(model, X_train, y_train, **kwargs)

    mean_scores = pd.DataFrame(scores).mean()
    std_scores = pd.DataFrame(scores).std()
    out_col = []

    for i in range(len(mean_scores)):
        out_col.append((f"%0.3f (+/- %0.3f)" % (mean_scores[i], std_scores[i])))

    return pd.Series(data=out_col, index=mean_scores.index)

X_train, y_train = (
    train_df.drop(columns=["default.payment.next.month"]),
    train_df["default.payment.next.month"],
)
X_test, y_test = (
    test_df.drop(columns=["default.payment.next.month"]),
    test_df["default.payment.next.month"],
)

dummy = DummyClassifier(strategy="most_frequent")
results["Dummy"] = mean_std_cross_val_scores(

Note that we are seeing a test_score and train_score of 0, which in this case makes sense because our dummy classifier is using the "most frequent" strategy, which means it will always predict "not default". This means that we will have a false positive rate of 0, and a true positive rate of 0, meaning our recall value would actually just be 0. In this case, our dummy classifier isn't too useful.

Looking at the test_scores, we can see that we are underfitting when the max_depth is under 5, and we start to overfit around max_depth of 15. This gives us an idea of how we could do our hyperparameter optimzation later on. Since we only have 1 hyperparameter to adjust, and we have seen high and low values for max_depth perform poorly compared to the linear model, it is unlikely that we will be able to beat it.

Conclusion¶

As we can see, our LGBMClassifier with best parameters is doing quite well. As a sanity check, we outperformed our baseline, so that's good to see. Additionally, our test data score is outperforming all other models, except the validation set version of the same model. This is to be expected, and the score drop isn't too large (0.706 vs 0.665), which is encouraging to see. All in all, this gives us good confidence in our model.

Other Ideas¶

There were a few things we could have tried in order to improve our model. For example, we did not attempt using SVC models, since it took too long for our machines. Though, given the many features our data had, it may not have been too useful.

We could have also tried engineering different features. From our feature importances, we could see that the new features we added did not show up as too important. Coming up with different, more important features may have improved our model even more.

Finally, we did choose to use recall as our metric. We had considered using precision or recall for our metric, but decided against them because they seemed to be very detrimental to interpretability. Since the assignment was open-ended, we decided with recall. But if in a real situation we were told that precision/f1/accuracy were better, using those would be more beneficial.
